1. **Class-level variable or method**: When applied to a variable or method inside a class, `static` means that it belongs to the class itself, not to any instance of the class. This means that there is only one copy of the variable or method, shared by all instances of the class.

Example:
```java
public class MyClass {
    public static int myVariable = 10;
    public static void myMethod() {
        System.out.println("Hello, world!");
    }
}
```
